\begin_layout Exercise*
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
I.6
\end_layout

\end_inset

Prove the Cantor Normal Form Theorem:
 Every non-zero ordinal 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 has a Cantor Normal Form (CNF),
 i.e.
\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset

it can be written as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\alpha=\omega^{\beta_{1}}\ell_{1}+\dots+\omega^{\beta_{n}}\ell_{n},\label{eq:cnf}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\geq\beta_{1}>\beta_{2}>\dots>\beta_{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq\ell_{i}<\omega$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover,
 this representation is unique.
 Show that if 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa$
\end_inset

 is an uncountable cardinal then 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{1}(\kappa)=\kappa$
\end_inset

 (this is called an epsilon ordinal),
 and there are 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa$
\end_inset

 epsilon ordinals below 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa$
\end_inset

.
 In particular,
 the first epsilon number,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{0}$
\end_inset

,
 is countable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
First,
 we show that every non-zero ordinal can be written as in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:cnf"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 To this effect,
 let 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 be the smallest counterexample,
 if any exists.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{1}$
\end_inset

 be the supremum element of the class 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\beta\mid\omega^{\beta}\leq\alpha\}$
\end_inset

 (this class is bounded by 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 because 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega^{\alpha}\geq\alpha$
\end_inset

 by transfinite induction,
 and nonempty because 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\geq\omega^{0}$
\end_inset

).
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega^{\beta_{1}}$
\end_inset

 is thus the supremum of 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega^{\beta}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 in this class,
 we therefore have 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega^{\beta_{1}}\leq\alpha$
\end_inset

,
 but also 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega^{\beta_{1}+1}>\alpha$
\end_inset

 as that'd contradict maximality of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
Now,
 let 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{1}$
\end_inset

 be the supremum of the class 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\ell\mid\omega^{\beta_{1}}\ell\leq\alpha\}$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly to before,
 this class is bounded from above – in fact,
 it's bounded from above by 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

.
 Thus,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\leq\omega$
\end_inset

.
 But,
 in fact,
 this class is finite,
 because 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha<\omega^{\beta_{1}+1}=\sup_{n<\omega}\omega^{\beta_{1}}n$
\end_inset

,
 and thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha<\omega^{\beta_{1}}n$
\end_inset

 for some particular 
\begin_inset Formula $n<\omega$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{1}<\omega$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
So,
 we know 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega^{\beta_{1}}\ell_{1}\leq\alpha$
\end_inset

,
 which implies that we may write 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=\omega^{\beta_{1}}\ell_{1}+\alpha_{0}$
\end_inset

 for some ordinal 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{0}\leq\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 (This is obvious from the interpretations of 
\begin_inset Formula $\leq$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

embeds as initial substructure
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $+$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

concatenate
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and the theorem 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

any well-order is isomorphic to an ordinal
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.) We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{0}<\alpha$
\end_inset

 – and,
 in fact,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{0}<\omega^{\beta_{1}}\leq\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed,
 the alternative is that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{0}\geq\omega^{\beta_{1}}$
\end_inset

,
 in which case 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=\omega^{\beta_{1}}\ell_{1}+\alpha_{0}\geq\omega^{\beta_{1}}\ell_{1}+\omega^{\beta_{1}}=\omega^{\beta_{1}}(\ell_{1}+1)$
\end_inset

,
 and so 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{1}$
\end_inset

 isn't minimal,
 a contradiction.
 Thus,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{0}$
\end_inset

 is either zero (in which case we just found an CNF for 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

),
 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{0}$
\end_inset

 has a CNF,
 which obviously provides a CNF for 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 (Minor detail:
 The coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{i}$
\end_inset

 are thus in decreasing order because,
 e.g.
\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{2}\leq\alpha_{0}<\omega^{\beta_{1}}\leq\beta_{1}$
\end_inset

,
 and so on inductively.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
Now,
 we need to establish uniqueness.
 We claim that,
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is written as 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:cnf"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 the ordinals 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{1}$
\end_inset

 
\emph on
must
\emph default
 be the ones we created in the previous paragraphs,
 which by induction on the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{0}$
\end_inset

 obtained by subtracting 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega^{\beta_{1}}\ell_{1}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 as in the previous paragraph,
 implies that the length of the decomposition and all ordinals therein must also be the same.
 The proof now goes:
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=\omega^{\beta_{1}}\ell_{1}+\omega^{\beta_{2}}\ell_{2}+\dots+\omega^{\beta_{n}}\ell_{n}$
\end_inset

 is some CNF decomposition.
 Then,
 either 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=\omega^{\beta_{1}}\ell_{1}<\omega^{\beta_{1}}(\ell_{1}+1)<\omega^{\beta_{1}+1}$
\end_inset

 (if the sequence has length 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

),
 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\leq\omega^{\beta_{1}}\ell_{1}+\omega^{\beta_{2}}(\ell_{2}+\dots+\ell_{n})<\omega^{\beta_{1}}(\ell_{1}+1)<\omega^{\beta_{1}+1}$
\end_inset

.
 In both cases,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\geq\omega^{\beta_{1}}\ell_{1}$
\end_inset

 obviously.
 In either case,
 we can quickly establish that 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{1}$
\end_inset

 is the supremum of the class 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\beta\mid\omega^{\beta}\leq\alpha\}$
\end_inset

,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{1}$
\end_inset

 is the supremum of the class 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\ell\mid\omega^{\beta_{1}}\ell\leq\alpha\}$
\end_inset

 (by using the previous inequalities to see that each ordinal is in the corresponding class but (ordinal
\begin_inset Formula $+1$
\end_inset

) is not),
 which thus establishes the desired uniqueness.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
Before proceeding,
 a brief word of epsilon ordinals.
 As we just saw,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{1}(\alpha)=\sup\{\beta\mid\omega^{\beta}\leq\alpha\}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus,
 an epsilon ordinal is precisely one that satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega^{\alpha}=\alpha$
\end_inset

;
 the implication 
\begin_inset Formula $(\rightarrow)$
\end_inset

 is because 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega^{\alpha}=\omega^{\sup\{\beta\mid\omega^{\beta}\leq\alpha\}}=\sup\{\omega^{\beta}\mid\omega^{\beta}\leq\alpha\}\leq\alpha\leq\omega^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

,
 and the implication 
\begin_inset Formula $(\leftarrow)$
\end_inset

 is because 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega^{\alpha+1}>\omega^{\alpha}\geq\alpha$
\end_inset

 always.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
OK,
 so,
 next,
 I need a lemma:
 The cardinality of 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 is always the same as the cardinality of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

,
 for infinite 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 This is an easy transfinite induction,
 using the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\card(\omega^{\alpha+1})=\card(\omega^{\alpha}\cdot\omega)=\card(\omega^{\alpha})\cdot\aleph_{0}=\card\omega^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 for the successor step,
 and the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa\cdot\kappa=\kappa$
\end_inset

 (cardinal arithmetic) is helpful for the limit step.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
Great,
 then,
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa$
\end_inset

 is an uncountable cardinal,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa\leq\omega^{\kappa}=\sup\{\omega^{\alpha}\mid\alpha<\kappa\}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa$
\end_inset

 is uncountable,
 we may as well take the supremum only over the infinite ordinals,
 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=\omega$
\end_inset

 will beat all of them,
 and since 
\begin_inset Formula $\card\omega^{\alpha}=\card\alpha<\kappa$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 in this supremum,
 we always have 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega^{\alpha}<\kappa$
\end_inset

,
 and so the supremum satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega^{\kappa}\leq\kappa$
\end_inset

.
 So,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa$
\end_inset

 is an epsilon ordinal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
Now,
 to show that there are 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa$
\end_inset

 many epsilon ordinals below 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa$
\end_inset

...
 I don't see a clever way to do this?
 So I'm going to sketch a heavy-handed way to do it.
 Would be happy to hear about a better approach.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
First,
 define a function on ordinals by transfinite recursion that satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\alpha+1)=\omega^{f(\alpha)}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\sup\alpha)=\sup f(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 (as a particular case,
 
\begin_inset Formula $f(0)=0$
\end_inset

).
 Intuitively,
 this is the tetration 
\begin_inset Formula $^{\alpha}\omega$
\end_inset

.
 Now,
 I claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 of a limit ordinal is always an epsilon ordinal,
 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega^{f(\gamma)}=\omega^{\sup_{\alpha<\gamma}f(\alpha)}=\sup_{\alpha<\gamma}\omega^{f(\alpha)}=\sup_{\alpha<\gamma}f(\alpha+1)\leq f(\gamma)\leq\omega^{f(\gamma)}$
\end_inset

 (in the penultimate step we used:
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha<\gamma$
\end_inset

,
 so is 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha+1$
\end_inset

,
 and also 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is monotonous).
 Moreover,
 a transfinite recursion will show that,
 for infinite ordinals,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\card f(\alpha)=\card\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 So,
 since there are 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa$
\end_inset

-many limit ordinals below 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa$
\end_inset

 (the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

multiply by 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 on the left
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 operation furnishes a bijection between 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa$
\end_inset

 and the set of said limit ordinals),
 there are therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa$
\end_inset

-many epsilon ordinals below 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa$
\end_inset

 – take these limit ordinals,
 apply 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

,
 and use the cardinality argument to show they're below 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

