\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\forall_{i\in I}\theta_{i}<\kappa_{i}\right)\rightarrow\sum_{i}\theta_{i}<\prod_{i}\kappa_{i}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Derive Konig's Lemma from (a).
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Solution
(a) It suffices to inject the disjoint union 
\begin_inset Formula $\amalg_{i}\theta_{i}$
\end_inset

 into the Cartesian product 
\begin_inset Formula $\times_{i}\kappa_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Well,
 the assumption that 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{i}>\theta_{i}$
\end_inset

 means that 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{i}$
\end_inset

 is always nonempty because they all contain 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

.
 So we can imagine the map that takes 
\begin_inset Formula $(i,t)\in\{i\}\times\theta_{i}$
\end_inset

 into the function 
\begin_inset Formula $j\mapsto\delta_{ij}(t+1)$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{ij}$
\end_inset

 is the Kronecker delta.
 This uses the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{i}<\kappa_{i}$
\end_inset

 to ensure that 
\begin_inset Formula $t+1$
\end_inset

 is in 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 This map is injective because we can recover 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 as the unique input that has a nonzero output,
 and we can recover 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 as the predecessor of said output (which always exists).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
(b) If 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa$
\end_inset

 is infinite and 
\begin_inset Formula $\cof(\kappa)\leq\lambda$
\end_inset

,
 then there is a sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\theta_{i}\}_{i<\lambda}$
\end_inset

 that is cofinal in 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa^{\lambda}=\prod_{i<\lambda}\kappa>\sum_{i<\lambda}\theta_{i}\geq\sup_{i<\lambda}\theta_{i}=\kappa$
\end_inset

,
 where the second step is because 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum\geq\sup$
\end_inset

 (all 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{i}$
\end_inset

 inject into the disjoint union and hence the sum is a common upper bound) and the third step is because the sequence is cofinal in 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

