Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\AR$
\end_inset

 denote the axiom of replacement,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\AR^{*}$
\end_inset

 the strengthening of 
\begin_inset Formula $\AR$
\end_inset

 to
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\forall_{x\in A}\exists_{y}\varphi(x,y,\vec{p})\rightarrow\exists_{B}\forall_{x\in A}\exists_{y\in B}\varphi(x,y,\vec{p}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise*
Show that every instance of 
\begin_inset Formula $\AR^{*}$
\end_inset

 is provable in 
\begin_inset Formula $\ZF$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
It would be cool if we could replace 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(x,y,\vec{p})$
\end_inset

 by the formula 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 is a minimal (in some sense) element that satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(x,y,\vec{p})$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

,
 because then we could straight-up apply normal replacement.
 But unless we can well-order the entire universe,
 this is not necessarily feasible.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
The next best thing is to replace 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(x,y,\vec{p})$
\end_inset

 by something such that,
 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{p}$
\end_inset

,
 is satisfied by a collection of things that fit in a set.
 This can be done:
 We replace 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(x,y,\vec{p})$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{+}(x,y,\vec{p})$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 is an element of minimal rank that satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(x,y,\vec{p})$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 This ensures that the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

image of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is contained in some finite level of the von
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Neumann hierarchy,
 and is therefore a set by comprehension.
 We denote the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

image of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $F(x,\vec{p})$
\end_inset

.
 Foundation ensures that 
\begin_inset Formula $\exists_{y}\varphi\rightarrow\exists_{y}\varphi_{+}$
\end_inset

,
 and thus,
 assuming 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall_{x\in A}\exists_{y}\varphi(x,y,\vec{p})$
\end_inset

,
 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in A$
\end_inset

 the set 
\begin_inset Formula $F(x,\vec{p})$
\end_inset

 is nonempty.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
To finish the proof:
 Assume 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall_{x\in A}\exists_{y}\varphi(x,y,\vec{p})$
\end_inset

,
 and construct 
\begin_inset Formula $B=\bigcup\{F(x,\vec{p})\mid x\in A\}$
\end_inset

.
 (We use union and replacement.) Then,
 the claim is that this set 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 satisfies the conclusion of 
\begin_inset Formula $\AR^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed,
 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in A$
\end_inset

 there is 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in F(x,\vec{p})$
\end_inset

 (by end of prevs.
 paragraph) and hence in 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

