\begin_inset Formula $\ZF$
\end_inset

,
 that if 
\begin_inset Formula $\class R$
\end_inset

 is a well-founded relation on 
\begin_inset Formula $\class A$
\end_inset

 (but possibly not set-like) then every non-empty subclass 
\begin_inset Formula $\class X$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\class A$
\end_inset

 has an 
\begin_inset Formula $\class R$
\end_inset

-minimal element.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\class R$
\end_inset

 is a relation on 
\begin_inset Formula $\class A$
\end_inset

,
 I can create a new relation via
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\class Q(x,y)\equiv\text{\ensuremath{x} is a minimal rank element with \ensuremath{\class R(x,y)}}.
\]

\end_inset

This new relation is guaranteed to be set-like because:
 Either 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 has no 
\begin_inset Formula $\class R$
\end_inset

-predecessors,
 in which case its 
\begin_inset Formula $\class Q$
\end_inset

-predecessor class is the empty set,
 or it has at least one 
\begin_inset Formula $\class R$
\end_inset

-predecessor,
 say of rank 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

,
 in which case its class of 
\begin_inset Formula $\class Q$
\end_inset

-predecessors is contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $R(\alpha)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
This new relation is guaranteed to be well-founded because:
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $X\subseteq\class A$
\end_inset

 is nonempty,
 it admits an element with no 
