\begin_layout Exercise*
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
III.20
\end_layout

\end_inset

Show,
 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\ZFC^{*}-\mathsf{P}$
\end_inset

,
 that if 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{n}$
\end_inset

 is countable for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n<\omega$
\end_inset

,
 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\cup_{n}A_{n}$
\end_inset

 is countable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
Begin from the assumption:
 For every 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\omega$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{n}$
\end_inset

 is countable.
 That is,
 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\omega$
\end_inset

,
 there is an injection from 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{n}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

.
 (I'm using the sense of countable that includes possibly finite.
 This is the harder case anyway – if any of the 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{n}$
\end_inset

 is infinite so is their union.) Then,
 we apply the stronger axiom of replacement 
\begin_inset Formula $\AR^{*}$
\end_inset

 to obtain:
 There is a set 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

,
 such that for every 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\omega$
\end_inset

,
 there is 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in B$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is an injection from 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{n}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

.
 Using 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsf{AC}$
\end_inset

,
 well-order 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

,
 and define 
\begin_inset Formula $\{f_{n}\}_{n\in\omega}$
\end_inset

 to be the least element of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 that is an injection from 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{n}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

.
 Thus,
 we obtain that the sets 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{n}$
\end_inset

 are uniformly countable (meaning:
 There is a (set) function which,
 given 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

,
 outputs an injection 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{n}\to\omega$
\end_inset

),
 from which we can very easily obtain an injection 
\begin_inset Formula $\cup_{n}A_{n}\to\amalg_{n}A_{n}\to\omega\times\omega\to\omega$
\end_inset

.
 (Where 
\begin_inset Formula $\amalg_{n}A_{n}$
\end_inset

 is the disjoint union of all 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{n}$
\end_inset

,
 meaning 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\braket{n,a}\mid n\in\omega,a\in A_{n}\}$
\end_inset

.)
\end_layout

